          "displayType": "poster",
          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>In the regulation of gastric acid secretion, which hormone acts as the negative </p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>In the regulation of gastric acid secretion, which hormone acts as the negative feedback signal that switches off gastrin release when acidity rises?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Secretin</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Secretin is released by duodenal S cells in response to acid entering the duodenum. It stimulates pancreatic bicarbonate secretion but does not directly inhibit gastrin release from G cells.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Cholecystokinin</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>CCK is released by I cells in response to fat and protein. It stimulates pancreatic enzyme secretion and gallbladder contraction, but does not participate in the gastrin feedback loop.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Somatostatin</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. When gastric acidity rises, D cells release somatostatin, which directly inhibits gastrin secretion from neighbouring G cells. This is the classic negative feedback loop controlling acid output.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Gastric inhibitory peptide</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>GIP (from duodenal K cells) suppresses gastric acid and stimulates insulin release, but it acts from the duodenum — it is not the local antral signal that directly switches off gastrin.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "Review the feedback pattern described in this section: gastrin drives acid secretion, and rising acidity activates somatostatin from D cells, which then switches gastrin off."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Well done. The gastrin–somatostatin negative feedback loop is a core regulatory mechanism: rising acidity activates D cells → somatostatin release → gastrin suppression → reduced acid output."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
