          },
          "pause": true,
          "displayType": "poster",
          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>Brunner's glands secrete alkaline mucus to protect the duodenal wall from gastri</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>Brunner's glands secrete alkaline mucus to protect the duodenal wall from gastric acid. What happens to these glands under chronic sympathetic stimulation (stress)?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>They increase their alkaline mucus output</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Sympathetic stimulation actually suppresses Brunner's gland activity. Increased output occurs with parasympathetic (vagal) stimulation.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>They are suppressed, reducing mucosal protection</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. Sympathetic tone dominates during stress, suppressing Brunner's glands. The duodenal mucosa loses its alkaline mucus shield, which is why duodenal ulcers are more common under chronic stress.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>They switch from mucus secretion to enzyme secretion</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Brunner's glands secrete only alkaline mucus; they do not produce digestive enzymes under any stimulus. The switch does not occur.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>They undergo hypertrophy and become overactive</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Chronic stress causes suppression, not hypertrophy, of Brunner's glands. Hypertrophy of Brunner's glands is a separate, rare pathological condition unrelated to sympathetic stimulation.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "Remember: vagal (parasympathetic) stimulation activates Brunner's glands, while sympathetic stimulation suppresses them. Under chronic stress, sympathetic dominance removes the alkaline mucus barrier, predisposing to duodenal ulcers."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Exactly right. The stress–ulcer link through Brunner's gland suppression is a classic example of how autonomic regulation directly affects mucosal defence."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
