          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>After digestion, chylomicrons assembled inside enterocytes are too large to ente</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>After digestion, chylomicrons assembled inside enterocytes are too large to enter blood capillaries. By which route do they reach the systemic circulation?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Portal vein → liver → hepatic vein</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The portal vein carries water-soluble nutrients (glucose, amino acids) to the liver. Chylomicrons are too large for blood capillary fenestrations and cannot use this route.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Mesenteric veins → inferior vena cava</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Mesenteric veins drain into the portal system and carry only water-soluble nutrients. Chylomicrons require the lymphatic route.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Lacteals → thoracic duct → left subclavian vein</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. Chylomicrons enter the lacteals (lymphatic capillaries inside villi), travel through lymphatic vessels to the thoracic duct, and empty into the bloodstream at the left subclavian vein — bypassing the liver entirely on first pass.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Hepatic artery → systemic circulation</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The hepatic artery delivers oxygenated blood to the liver; it plays no role in nutrient absorption from the gut.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "Remember: fat takes the lymphatic route because chylomicrons are physically too large for blood capillaries. They enter lacteals in the villi, travel via the thoracic duct, and join the bloodstream at the left subclavian vein."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Well done. The lymphatic route for fat (lacteals → thoracic duct → subclavian vein) is a key distinction from the portal route used by carbohydrates and proteins."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
