          },
          "pause": true,
          "displayType": "poster",
          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>A patient with cholera has profuse watery diarrhoea that persists even when fast</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>A patient with cholera has profuse watery diarrhoea that persists even when fasting. Which type of diarrhoea does this represent?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Osmotic diarrhoea</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Osmotic diarrhoea is caused by unabsorbed solutes drawing water into the lumen. It characteristically stops with fasting because the osmotic load is removed. Cholera diarrhoea persists during fasting.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Secretory diarrhoea</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. In cholera, the toxin activates adenylyl cyclase in enterocytes, causing sustained chloride and water secretion regardless of oral intake. The hallmark of secretory diarrhoea is that it persists during fasting.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Inflammatory diarrhoea</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Inflammatory diarrhoea produces blood and pus (mucoid/bloody stools), as seen in dysentery or inflammatory bowel disease. Cholera produces rice-water stools without blood.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Malabsorptive diarrhoea</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Malabsorptive diarrhoea produces fatty, floating stools (steatorrhoea) due to failure to absorb nutrients. This is not the mechanism in cholera.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "The four types differ by mechanism: secretory (persists with fasting — active secretion, e.g. cholera), osmotic (stops with fasting — unabsorbed solutes), inflammatory (blood and pus), and malabsorptive (fatty stools). Use the fasting test to distinguish secretory from osmotic."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Exactly. The key distinguishing feature: secretory diarrhoea persists during fasting (active ion secretion), while osmotic diarrhoea stops (no osmotic load). Cholera is the classic secretory example."
                }
              ],
